By: Brian C Kiedrowski<br>
<br>
Every society since the dawn of humanity has related its basic values and beliefs through their artful expression.  Although the term mythology seems anachronistic, centuries from now, future humans may look back upon our books, movies, television shows, and other publications to paint a historical picture of our culture and belief systems. <br>
<br>
 Modern historians have used the mythos of extinct cultures to extract a bit about their comprehension of the world.  Through Greek mythology, we can see what the people of ancient Greece believed.  To them, Apollo rode around on his Sun Chariot everyday and Zeus threw his lightning bolts whenever he was angry.  Today we look upon the Greeks amusingly as we know the Earth orbits the sun and lightning bolts are caused by differences in charges built up between clouds and the ground.  Although we think we may have a wonderful understanding of the universe, future generations will undoubtedly chuckle at our ignorance.<br>
<br>
One of the greatest myths of the 20th century falls to radiation.  Future historians are likely to watch movies where radiation has created giant mutant creatures of some sort or another.  They are likely to read comics and see the whole radiation induced superpowers mythos.  Although scientists and those more educated know these effects of radiation are utterly ludicrous, as probably some Greek philosophers probably hypothesized about their myths, the brightest are often not indicative of the culture as a whole.<br>
<br>
Although the above examples are a bit far fetched, the radiation mythology has spread throughout non-entertainment publications.  Many people still believe that any form or amount of radiation is harmful and will try (and unknowingly fail) to avoid it at all costs.  Unbeknownst to many, everyone is showered in a nice bath of ionizing radiation every day.  Most of the radiation humans receive comes from totally natural sources that have been around since before the first land animal crawled out of the ocean.<br>
<br>
But what is radiation?  This question does not have a simple answer really.  Radiation comes from many sources.  Everything on the electromagnetic spectrum ranging from radio waves, to microwaves, to visible light, to ultraviolet, to x-rays, to those dreaded gamma rays.  These can be divided up into two categories: ionizing and non-ionizing.  <br>
<br>
Basically, when a light wave (called a photon) hits an atom, it causes electrons to “jump” away from the nucleus.  Think of a person jumping up and falling back down to Earth.  When the electron falls back to its original state, (called the ground state) it tends to emit another photon and the process continues.<br>
<br>
How high the electron jumps depends on how powerful the original photon was to begin with.  Photons in the higher ultraviolet and x-ray range have enough power to launch an electron away from the atom.  This process is called ionization.  When something is ionized, it is missing an electron.  What this means is the atom becomes chemically active and will readily react with other atoms in its surroundings.  This tends not be good as it changes the chemical composition of the molecules in our bodies.<br>
<br>
Another kind of radiation comes from nuclear sources.  Certain nuclei tend to be unstable and not want to stick together.  Eventually, these particles will fall apart and decay.  There are three basic modes of decay that exist:  Alpha, Beta, and Gamma.<br>
<br>
Larger atoms like Uranium or Plutonium tend to undergo alpha decay.  Basically, the nucleus gives off what is called an alpha particle.  The alpha particle consists of two protons and two neutrons – this is essentially a helium ion because it has no electrons.  This particle is quite massive and can cause quite a bit of damage.  However, alpha particles have a very short range.  If your computer screen were emitting alpha particles right now, very few of them would even reach you.  A sheet of paper is enough to block out most of the alpha particles.  The major threats from these come when they are ingested or inhaled.  Inside your body, they can cause quite a bit of damage.  Outside, they are virtually harmless.  One could hold a bar of Uranium with gloved hands for a long time and experience no ill effects.<br>
<br>
Beta particles are emitted by smaller atoms like Potassium, Cesium, Carbon-14 and many others.  A beta particle is simply a very energetic and fast moving electron.  These beta particles are smaller and can penetrate deeper into skin.  However, they are also less damaging than alpha particles.  Beta particles are fairly easy to shield and some thick aluminum foil could easily do the trick.<br>
<br>
Gamma rays are very energetic photons like x-rays.  The difference is these photons are emitted directly from the nucleus and not from the electron.  After a nucleus undergoes any nuclear reaction, it tends to be very excited.  It has to relieve itself by ejecting a very powerful photon called a gamma ray.  These gamma rays are very penetrating and require a thick sheet of lead or many feet of concrete to effectively block.  The good news is gamma rays do very little damage in the long run and unless you get hit by a lot of them, there is little danger.<br>
<br>
There is a fourth kind of radiation that comes in the form of neutrons.  When atoms split or fission, some of their neutrons break off and become free.  These neutrons quickly move through matter going through anything in its way as if it were not there.  Occasionally, one of the neutrons might hit another nucleus and may bond to it.  This can often cause the atom to become radioactive itself.  Neutrons are the main direct threat from nuclear reactors and can be quite deadly.  Fortunately, free neutrons are relatively quite rare in daily life and pose little threat.<br>
<br>
So radiation changes the chemistry inside our body; that must be bad right?  Well, it can be, in sufficiently high doses.  What we need is a way to measure and evaluate the biological effectiveness of radiation exposure.  A common unit for the biologically effective radiation dose is called the rem.  The rem is a fairly large unit for measuring radiation.  On average, a person receives about one-third of a rem per year, or 300-400 millirem (mrem; a thousandth of a rem).  This measure represents what is often called “annual natural background” or “natural background” and is often useful for describing how much radiation a person actually receives.<br>
<br>
Inevitably, the question of how much radiation is harmful comes up.  Unfortunately, there is no easy way to answer this question. We know that about 500 rem (or roughly 1500 times the annual natural background) is the half-death rate.  This means that if we exposed a room full of people to 500 rem of radiation apiece, roughly half of them would die.  Any dose higher than 1000 rem would almost certainly kill anyone exposed.  These sudden doses are called ‘acute doses’, which mean a large dose in a short period of time.  <br>
<br>
We know these are deadly, but how about smaller doses over a long period of time?  As I stated above, knowledge on this is fair, but not as great as we would like as the effects tend to minimal.  Much of what we know about radiation exposure comes from after the Hiroshima and Nagasaki bombings in World War II.  Although horrific events, they gave scientists a chance to study the long-term effects of varying amounts of radiation exposure.  From all studies done, including the studies of the bombings, no harmful effects were found for people exposed to less than 65 times the annual natural background.  This means that there was not a statistically significant increase in the death rate of from those who were not exposed to the bomb radiation i.e. there were some cancer deaths among those who received less than 65 times natural background; however, they were not enough for the scientists to determine whether or not they were actually induced by the bomb radiation.<br>
<br>
So how can we measure how much damage a particular dose of radiation does to a person.  As with most other physical systems, scientists have devised a few models.  A common method is called the linear-no threshold model.  The linear-no threshold model postulates that if a large dose of radiation can kill 100 people, half that dose will kill 50, one-fourth will kill 25, and so on all the way down to zero.  The linear-no threshold model believes that ANY amount of radiation is harmful no matter how small.  Although there is much evidence that large doses of radiation behave this way, there is active debate on how smaller doses behave.<br>
<br>
The linear-no threshold model is based upon extrapolations and thought experiments about current biological models.  Although this is, on face, a good way to measure radiological effects, it does not necessarily mean it is applicable to the real world.  A model is only effective if it can effectively describe the real world correctly.  Although the linear-no threshold describes the effects of large doses well, it does not fair so well for smaller doses.  Many more modern and rigorous studies show that small doses of radiation are harmless or even beneficial – this theory is called radiation hormesis.<br>
<br>
There is a good degree of evidence to support this claim.  A study at the Argonne National Lab showed a 15% lower cancer death rate for western states with natural background twice as high as those in the other 41 states.  Studies in the US, Japan, and China show that homes with five times the normal radon levels actually have lower cancer rates.  Another study compared the death rates of two groups between 1960 and 1982 of shipyard workers who worked on nuclear submarines.  One ground of 28,000 received radiation exposure from radioactive materials whereas another ground of 33,000 of similar age did not.  Although there was no difference in cancer rates between the two groups, the nuclear workers were healthier than those who were not exposed having a 24% lower death rate from all causes than those who received none.<br>
<br>
Although counter-intuitive, how can small radiation doses actually be beneficial?  This is currently an area of medical research, however, much data has already accumulated.  Current theories suggest that small amounts of ionizing radiation activate certain molecules in the cell nucleus that help repair damaged DNA.  Throughout life, our DNA gets damaged due to exposure to chemicals and radiation.  However, radiation actually stimulates the certain molecules in the cell causing them to repair this damage.  This makes some sense from an evolutionary standpoint as well.  Life evolved under a constant bath of radiation.  Those with cells more resistant to radiation doses were more likely to survive than those who did not have such resistances.<br>
<br>
Scientific studies seem to show that the linear-no threshold model is not applicable to smaller doses of radiation exposure.  Despite this, the National Council on Radiation Protection and Measurements, a group that calculates radiation doses and advises the US government on safety, still uses the linear-no threshold model to do their calculations.  US government agencies use this model to determine the effects of radiological doses due to nuclear accidents and general radiation exposure.<br>
<br>
Although this seems a bit contradictory to the meaning of science, it is not all that surprising.  People tend to cling to their old models until something comes along to shatter it.  Take for instance Aristotle’s hypothesis that heavier things fall faster than lighter things.  Although this worldview worked fine for a falling stone and a sheet of papyrus – clearly the stone will beat an uncrumpled sheet of paper every time as anyone can easily verify.  However, if the same experiment is carried out in a vacuum both will fall at the same rate because of the lack of air resistance.  This clearly demonstrates that Aristotle’s hypothesis was incorrect for more “exotic” cases.  Another example is Ptolemy’s epicycle model (which Aristotle supported) of the solar system that set Earth at the center.  To explain the retrograde motion of the planets (as the Earth passed the more distant planets) Ptolemy proposed a model where the planets actually made a circle.  As time passed, this model required more and more epicycles to do corrections over time.<br>
<br>
Both of these models survived for over a millennium.  Even after more sensible ideas came to light, the followers of the old Aristotle mythology continued to support it for some time.  This is similar to the current radiation mythology that groups continue to support despite evidence that was gained in the past decade to the contrary.  There are two reasons for this maintenance of the current belief system.<br>
<br>
The first reason is purely pragmatic.  The linear-no threshold model is a lot easier than a model that requires a threshold.  The first issue has to due with the threshold itself; where do you put it?  Although we can be pretty sure the linear-no threshold model is invalid for small exposures, where to we place the dividing line between small exposures and ones where the linear-no threshold model becomes applicable?  This is not an easy question to answer and will merit much more study before the issue can be resolved.  A secondary concern is the ease of the calculation itself.  It is simply a lot easier to add a bunch of numbers than it is to account for some kind of threshold and what negative (or positive) effect curve it may have (i.e. it could exponential, logarithmic, containing step functions, etc.).  The possibly complicated curve could make doing calculations difficult, even though they would be more accurate.<br>
<br>
The other reason primarily comes from the nuclear culture itself.  Over the past half-century, people within the field have taken great strides to minimize any form of exposure or injury.  The nuclear industry has the lowest per capita injury occurrences of any other major industry.  In fact, you are more likely to get injured working in an office than you are at a nuclear plant.  The moral of the story is the linear-no threshold theory represents an absolute maximum damage due to the radiation.  It is simply impossible to have more damage given the amount of each radiation.  For instance, if one million people get each exposed to one-millionth of a lethal dose that would mean at most one person would die.  There is no way more than one person could die in this situation as a simple logical argument could explain.<br>
<br>
The linear-no threshold model yields much of the radiation mythology of our time.  It gives us strange results like the million people each receiving one-millionth of the lethal dose.  The linear-no threshold model says that one person will die; in fact, it requires it.  Using the linear-no threshold model, you can reach some pretty ridiculous results.  For instance, each person gets about 30 millirems from solar radiation assuming no over-exposure such as sunburns that would increase cancer rates.  Multiply that by six billion people at a 1000 rem lethality rate, and you will find that solar radiation kills 180,000 people every year without a single sunburn.  <br>
<br>
